description: From Middle English kempe (“coarse hairs”), from Old English cenep (“moustache; bit (of a bridle, bristling with points)”), from Proto-West Germanic *kanip, from Proto-Germanic *kanipaz (“beard, moustache, whiskers”), from Proto-Indo-European *ǵénus (“jaw”). Related to camp, chin.

entries.meaning: (obsolete or dialectal) Coarse, rough hair, wool, or fur; (in the plural) knotty hairs that will not felt.

description: From Middle English kempe, campe (“shaggy, rough”).

adjectives.description: kemp (comparative more kemp, superlative most kemp)

description: From Middle English kempen, from Old English *cempan (“to do battle, fight”), from Proto-West Germanic *kampijan (“to campaign, do battle”), ultimately from Latin campus.

entries.meaning: (Scotland, archaic) A contest in work, etc.

verbs.description: kemp (third-person singular simple present kemps, present participle kemping, simple past and past participle kemped)

entries.meaning: (intransitive, obsolete) To strive or contend in any way; strive for victory.

description: From Middle English kempe, from Old English cempa (“warrior, fighter, champion”), from Proto-West Germanic *kampijō (“fighter”), ultimately from Latin campus. Doublet of champion. Cognate with literary German Kämpe (“champion, fighter”), German Kempf.
